05173nam a22009255i 9783110492385DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20162016gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2017287307  a(OCoLC)1006797235  a97831104923857 a10.1515/97831104923852doi  a(DE-B1597)469139  a(OCoLC)954123393  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aPL1129.E5bP36 2016 4aPL1129.E5bP36 2016 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a495.1/82421223  aEG 92002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/23414:1 aPan, Victor Junnan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aResumptivity in Mandarin Chinese :bA Minimalist Account /cVictor Junnan Pan. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (XV, 308 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v29800tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tList of abbreviations -- t1. Resumptivity: an overview -- t2. Syntactic derivation: two types of A’-dependencies -- t3. Reconstruction and internal structures of resumptive pronouns -- t4. Specificity effects -- t5. Concluding remarks -- t6. Appendix: General distribution of the resumptive pronouns in Mandarin Chinese -- tReferences -- tSubject index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe use of resumptive pronouns is quite productive in Mandarin Chinese; however, their distribution has rarely been studied in a systematic way. This book not only gives a thorough description of the general distribution of resumptive pronouns in different contexts but also offers a theoretical account in the framework of the Minimalist Program. Different types of A'-dependencies, mediated by gaps and by resumptive pronouns, are derived by different minimalist mechanisms, such as Agree, Match and Move. These mechanisms only apply at Narrow Syntax and do not uniformly obey locality constraints. Importantly, interpretative properties of an A'-bound element, such as reconstruction effects, is only related to its internal structure irrespective of how the A'-chain concerned is derived. From this perspective, resumptivity is an exclusively syntactic-related phenomenon and is thus not subject to any interface condition. Adopting a comparative approach, this study improves the general understanding of resumptivity crosslinguistically.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChinese language. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxPronoun. 0aMandarin dialects. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aMandarin Chinese.  aMinimalist Program.  aResumptive Pronoun.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2016 Part 1z978311076250108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter Mouton Contemporary 2016-2019z978311074297808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2016z9783110485257oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97831104897500 cprintz978311048759640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311049238540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110492385423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110492385/original  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-070100-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-074297-8  De Gruyter Mouton Contemporary 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-076250-1  DG Plus DeG Package 2016 Part 1b